column1: Before 1 January 2022, will a commercial, open to the public, ride-hailing service that uses autonomous vehicles without back-up drivers nor remote operators be launched in the People's Republic of China?
column6: ['Business', 'Technology']
Give it five years, then we talk.
Not happening this year, for sure!
No - technology is not yet reliable or safe enough to operate without human activity intervention
given the logical format includes remote backup drivers, it is clear that this will likely never happen.
Technology is not mature enough yet. Chinese gov will be careful before rolling out to avoid backlashes, esp. as it is currently reining in big tech operators.

There's multiple companies testing autonomous cars in China currently, with billions at their disposal. However, the chances of them being operational with a fleet large enough to handle public demand, before the start of 2022, is incredibly small. The earliest that public testing could go live would be around March 2022.
I3 months is a short timeline, however Baidu reported level 4 on the road in taxi service with "backup" driver. I am going to up my prediction to 5%, but I think that March is the date.

I am with Colorkarma on this. The AutoX RoboTaxi trials IMHO show better promise than Tesla and are being trialled with no drivers in much more messy parts of China than Palo Alto, and the videos seem to indicate a much more resilient decision making process than the Tesla FSD betas despite the larger Tesla datasets.

Also, for fear of negative PR, no trials without remote operators will happen due to accidents then being able to be blamed on individual supervisors rather than incompletely developed driving system.

Baidu launches Apollo Go robotaxis in Beijing in the area of Shougang Park before a wider rollout in time for the Olympics. A number of developers are currently testing driverless, Level 4 taxis in geofenced areas, but a wider debut remains far on the horizon. Uber and Lyft have dropped autonomous research units entirely, selling them to cut costs, which indicates how close they think robotaxis really are to wider deployment. https://www.autoweek.com/news/technology/a36354137/beijing-olympics-robotaxi-china/

Germany is said to be developing its own too, 'beating China and the US.' But it's really hard to see one without remote control capabilities or remote monitoring; heck, it doesn't make sense to have just remote monitoring if you cannot remote control in case something happens. In the following article, the author writes, "Under the law, a technical command center would be tasked with overseeing the fleet remotely should any trouble ensue." If Germany has such a law in place, why would China not follow similarly both as a logical reason but also as a proxy. Still, anything can happen in China.
https://www.forbeschina.com/business/%E5%95%86%E4%B8%9A/55153
The technology is not ready yet

Not willing to pay for technology and they are going with their own developement, I doubt that whatever they have copied is too anticuated already. You need better process to keep leapoing forward with tech and the tests.

Baidu has started running ten driverless taxis in Beijing, but they have "safety monitors" in the front passenger seat in case things start to go badly. Presumably this doesn't count, but it may up the odds on something happening by next year. Coming up gradually and reluctantly, because I'm probably wrong about the time frame.

With the crowd on this one. I find it fascinating that all of these companies are working together to get this done. Motional, the joint venture between Hyundai and Aptiv; Pony.ai and Toyota; Blackberry and Baidu. Granted, there are still a lot of government regulations that are going to be needed to approve and give the final blessing on true "driverless" cars for commercial ride-hailing. I changed my mind. Like with many other questions on GJO, again with conjunction fallacy in mind. With so many requirements to YES and the majority of questions resolving NO, this is not a convincing event to occur. For now, I am also going to trust our local China forecasters on this one. However, I am aware that experts in a particular domain can be more wrong than the non-expert. I think my current probability forecast sits between the expert judgement and crowd judgement, which tend to be overconfident.

Coin-flip chance of tech avail but no approval, CF chance no tech at all meets criteria, CF chance there is a delay (say planning fallacy or any other kind of delay), CF chance approved for YES resolution, slightly likely chance tech is developed and approved but not for public use with payment, in respect to previous analyses.

China now has six companies that are approved to test driverless (no "in-car" driver) cars in both PRC and the United States. However, all of the companies are still required to have "remote operators" in case of emergency. https://www.theverge.com/2021/1/27/22252944/baidu-driverless-cars-test-permit-california-dmv

Hattip to @Fueled_by_Gummybears for finding the article bellow about a draft law allowing testing on highways.

New legislation by Beijing to allow for testing on busier roads means the government is likely more open about the idea of autonomous vehicles than I originally thought. That being said, after reading about the difference in bus service on a controlled road compared to a taxi service on a highway without a remote operator, I am lowering the outcome. Although I still believe this will be likely somewhere in the PRC on a small scale. https://www.intelligenttransport.com/transport-news/114787/china-autonomous-vehicle-laws/
I think I let my initial overenthisiasm get the better of me, so updating.
Hattip @xuehuisz for rationale that got me to change my forecast. Is it possible in 2021, maybe. Is it likely in 2021 less so. Going first brings acclaim unless it goes bad.
Not yet prepared for that. More time required.

I think it is very unlikely, reasons are: 1) China's hidden unemployment rate is pretty high, this is a very controversial topic, and no accurate data can be obtained, but judging from number of package delivering guys all around big cities in China, (Meituan 美团，Shunfeng 顺丰 etc）, and armies of Didi (滴滴打车）drivers who can be booked via smartphone apps, there are millions of people who can only find simple jobs such as above. Mostly young males. Even if the technology is ready, government would be very cautious of approving it. 2) So far, there are no level 5 autonomous driving cars on the market. Car makers had made lots of over optimistic predictions, but so far, no one. 3)The driving conditions in China is even more complex in US, packaging delivery guys riding electric bicycles never follow the traffic rule, and they move so fast, without noise (one advantage or disadvantage of electric bicycles), Old people never follow the traffic rule. Many drivers don't follow the rule strictly, for example, at least half drivers in Shenzhen (the city I live in) don't turn on direction lights before they turn. And many would drive faster than allowed or driving on emergency lanes, as long as there is no camera.
China intends to dominate global (EM) smart-cities

Bumping up because it is unlikely in the first half of the year, reports say they'll need six months of real world testing, probably outside of China itself, before they'll be opened to the Chinese public.
Commercial Autonomous ride-hailing services, as described in the question, are highly unlikely due to the lack of laws and regulations currently in place to govern the legal issues that will arise.
eHang will probably launch such a service for airborne eVTOLs by the end of 2021
I think deep learning alone without general ai is unlikely to achieve full inner city self driving. However a more limited version (highways only, very specific areas) may qualify for this question.
Hattip @BrianL for the reference succinctly defining the possibilities for a program in Beijing to allow robo-taxis at the 2022 Winter Olympics (04 FEB - 20 FEB 2022).
It will be approved in China before that in the USA

Autonomous driving is an open ended complex task which is impossible without remote operators to do: situations rise where the car just don't know what to do. The task is so complex that in two years such a service won't be open to public with remote operators either.
Technology isn't there,yet.

The announcement is seen as a step to have Robotaxis available for the 2022 Winter Olympics hosted in the city. Applicants must test their vehicles in closed areas for 5,000 kilometers before they are allowed onto public roads. In addition, a minimum of 1 million RMB (around 143,000 dollars) insurance must be purchased for each volunteer in the testing if the company would like to apply for a permit to transport customers. Which is unavoidable if companies would like to test drive on public roads as commercial activities are not allowed for the testing period, meaning they must have volunteers for test driving, thus must have insurance.

Reducing my forecast because I realize that a lot of the conditions that exist in Arizona for Google to do their right sharing service probably do not exist in China. Google is probably relying heavily on having roads that are well mapped out by Google maps.

An excellent summary article offered by @Fueled_by_Gummybears https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/03/tech/autox-robotaxi-china-intl-hnk/index.html Suggests that it may be near a time when the technology is ready, but the regulation and the public must also be ready. It's not clear how or when all the conditions are in place for this to take place. In 2023 the answer might be YES, in 2021, I am skeptical and don't believe a commercial service open to all will be launched, but perhaps, service limited to company employees may be put in place. Weather and traffic conditions in Beijing are not the same as in San Jose or Shenzhen. 8 is a lucky number in China, seems appropriate for this question at this time. 364 days to go.

It sounds like they're very close. But one of the main competitors, AutoX, which just got approval for autonomous vehicles with no backup driver in Shenzen, says in the linked article they intend to obtain permission to expand to regular passengers in the next 2 to 3 years. Other companies currently have to have backup drivers. I'm not sure why the long timeframe. Waymo has recently started offering taxi service in the US in autonomous vehicles with no backup driver. Maybe Waymo is just that much farther ahead?
I think even a 1 in 6 chance is a little generous, even for China.

I think the odds are good that Baidu, AutoX and the other competitors in this zone will feel confident that their technologies are ready within 2021, and regulatory issues will be addressed (or close to it). However, for most of 2021 I think the data will be significantly more valuable than any potential service fees they could gather from their R&D fleets, so they won't bother to charge for the rides. (The infrastructure for charging customers might be more expensive than the revenue earned.)
They can do anything. Did you see the way they built 1000s bed hospitals during Covid crisis.
Road safety concerns and insurance liability issues will not be resolved so soon.
Elon Maks is pushing with the fully self-driving car. China would like to be first and it is ready to reduce safety requirements in its own country.

Unlikely because autonomous vehicle technology combined with all of the other necessary software may not be ready yet.

China will not allow unemployment in their country to increase. They will try/test it out locally but will deploy the technology to the rest of the World

So we’ve got Waymo (Alphabet) that has taxis in San Jose. Baidu has service (with safety drivers) in Shanghai. AutoX (Ali Baba) that has auto taxi service in Shenzhen and San Jose. According to the CNN article, this is the first time they’ve fully removed the driver. I’m thinking at least one more year until its good enough to fully remove the driver AND the remote operator, and become a paying service. Looks like many are free right now just to get people used to the idea. https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/03/tech/autox-robotaxi-china-intl-hnk/index.html
Although there is an outside shot for this hitting to market within 12 months, it is more likely too short a timeframe to have moved from pilot projects to commercial
Due to lack of sensors and solutions for ethical problems autonomous Driving in cities will need 10+ years to be realised.
Given that Waymo has already rolled out something like this (on an extremely small scale) and there are multiple Chinese players involved, I expect to see a nominal Chinese equivalent crop up soon.

China is eager to demonstrate its leadership in technology and innovation. With other autonomous vehicle actors stepping aside, this would be a feather in their cap. This does not necessarily mean that they will be successful for long.
Will look into that, but human life is less of a concern in some places, so why not

The technology is there. The real question is the amount of testing to be done, and other sort of regulations that the Chinese government will want to add to it. It would be a mistake to use public data published in China about their progress, so honestly one can only guess.
unlikely before three years
Maybe in limited capacity in Shanghai, but likelihood of even that is low. Infrastructure with autonomous vehicles is highly underrated.
China will want to be a first as a matter of prestige.
Possible that we see a service like this launched in a bespoke environment, perhaps with geofencing, given this would lower the technological threshold

Part of the global leadership that China is exercising is to project itself with innovation, and they have all ready to do this project. So expect a parade of AVs if only for show in a limited environment.

The articles make this sounds imminent, but one article I read (https://edition.cnn.com/2020/12/03/tech/autox-robotaxi-china-intl-hnk/index.html) says that the company hopes to have paying customers "in two to three years" and I think the press frequently over-hypes how imminent driverless car advances are. Plus there seem to be endless delays for driverless cars, which keep having dates promised for widespread use which don't happen. Missing one more year seems a low bar.

Hard to try to put numbers on this, but the articles linked suggest that this is more of a regulatory than tech issue (at least in the sense that they already have the tech, just only available to certain people; it may well be a bad idea that goes wrong when implemented). It feels like the Chinese government will be keen to do this for the headlines/victory and approving it for a small city is probably not seen as a big risk to the Chinese government overall.
It's still early in the development of the technology and its application in real world traffic for the Chinese government to allow robot-taxis without back-up drivers or remote operators.
